{{Infobox Newspaper | name = Jornal dos Sports | image = | caption = | type = Regional daily sports [[newspaper]] | format = [[Broadsheet]] | owners = | foundation = {{start date and years ago|1931|03|13|mf=yes}} | ceased publication = {{start date and years ago|2010|04|10|mf=yes}} | price = 1.00 R$ | publisher = [[Editora dos Sports Ltda.]] | editor = | language = [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] | political = | circulation = 30,000 (2004)<ref name="circulation">{{pt icon}} [http://www.canaldaimprensa.com.br/canalant/foco/trint3/foco4.htm ''Chute na trave'' - Canal da Imprensa] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070714091101/http://www.canaldaimprensa.com.br/canalant/foco/trint3/foco4.htm |date=2007-07-14 }} (August 22, 2004)</ref> | headquarters = [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Rio de Janeiro (state)|RJ]], [[Brazil]] | website = [https://web.archive.org/web/20070507042326/http://jsports.uol.com.br/ jsports.uol.com.br] }}
'''''Jornal dos Sports''''' was a traditional [[Brazil]]ian sports newspaper from [[Rio de Janeiro]] which was published between March 13, 1931 and April 10, 2010. It was the oldest Brazilian daily sports newspaper, distributed mainly in [[Rio de Janeiro (state)|Rio de Janeiro state]].
''Jornal dos Sports'' was well known in Brazil for its distinctive pink paper, similar to that of the Italian ''[[La Gazzetta dello Sport]]''.
Among ''Jornal dos Sports'' most famous previous owners is [[Mário Filho]], after whom the [[Estádio do Maracanã|Maracanã Stadium]] is named.
