{{Infobox Organization |name = Korea American Football Association |image = Kafa logo.gif |image_border = |size = 150px |caption = Korea American Football Association's logo |map = |msize = |mcaption = |motto = |formation = 1945 |extinction = |type = Non-profit |headquarters = [[Seoul]] |location = |membership = |language = Korean (KR) |leader_title = Chairman |leader_name = Park Kyung-Kyu |key_people = |num_staff = |budget = |website = [http://kafa.org/ KAFA.org] }} The '''Korea American Football Association''' ('''KAFA''', [[Korean language|Korean]]: 대한미식축구협회, [[Hanja]]: 大韓美式蹴球協會) has existed in [[South Korea]] for more than 20 years. The popularity of [[American football]] in Korea has been historically low, but with the visit of [[Hines Ward]] (a Korean born NFL football star with the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]]) in 2006, the sport received a modest level of increased appeal. Within Korea, KAFA is a [[sports governing body]] over both traditional football with pads and also [[flag football]].
Traditional football [[Sports league|leagues]] within Korea are divided between university and senior (KNFL) teams. There are three championship bowl games of special note that occur at the end of the season. The Tiger Bowl determines the champions of the University league, the Gwangaeto Bowl determines the champions of the KNFL, and finally the [[Kimchi Bowl]], the Korean equivalent of Japan's [[Rice Bowl]], pits the University champion against the KNFL champion.
==College Programs== {|class="wikitable sortable" style="text-align: center;" |- !Institution !한국어 !Location !Founded !Type !Enrollment !Nickname !Colors
|- |[[Dong-eui University]] |동의대학교 |[[Busan]] |1977 |[[Private university|Private]] |22,992 |[[Dongeui Turtle Fighters football|Turtle Fighters]] |Red and White
|- |[[Yonsei University]] |연세대학교 |[[Seoul]] |1977 |[[Private university|Private]] |38,725 |[[Yonsei Eagles football|Eagles]] |Royal Blue |}
==KNFL==
In 2015, there were seven teams in the KNFL, divided into two divisions (북부리그 North Division, 남부리그 South Division). The top two seeds of each division played in a four-team semifinal playoffs. Winners of the semifinals played in the Gwanggaeto Bowl Championship. The KNFL Champion played the Korean University League Champion in the Kimchee Bowl.
Starting in 2016, the KNFL has changed to a full league format. Each of the seven teams play one another. The two teams with the best regular season records face off in the Gwanggaeto Bowl. The KNFL Champion plays the Korean University League Champion in the Kimchi Bowl.
