{{Infobox cricket ground | ground_name = Tyler's Ground | nickname = Tyler's Meadow | country = England | image = General view of the rough location of Tyler's Ground.jpg | caption = A general view of the rough location of Tyler's Ground | location = [[Loughborough]], [[Leicestershire]] | establishment = {{circa|1856}} | coord = {{coord|52.7781|-1.1888|display=inline}} | seating_capacity = | end1 = | end2 = | year1 = 1875 | club1 = [[North of England cricket team|North]] | date = 24 August | year = 2010 | source = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/607.html Ground profile }}
'''Tyler's Ground''' (also known as '''Tyler's Meadow''') was a [[cricket]] ground in [[Loughborough]], [[Leicestershire]]. It is believed the ground was located along Allsop's Lane on the edge of the town, with the ground being described as located a short distance from [[Loughborough railway station]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/607.html|title=Ground profile: Tyler's Ground, Loughborough|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=21 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.lboro.ac.uk/blog/culture/cricket-at-loughborough|title=Cricket at Loughborough|last=Whetnall|first=Barbara|date=7 July 2009|publisher=[[Loughborough University]]|accessdate=21 January 2013}}</ref> The first recorded match played at the ground was in 1856, when Loughborough played an [[All-England Eleven]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/607_misc.html|title=Other matches played on Tyler's Ground, Loughborough|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=21 January 2013}}</ref> A single [[first-class cricket|first-class]] match was played at the ground in 1875, when the [[North of England cricket team|North]] played the [[South of England cricket team|South]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/607_f.html|title=First-Class Matches played on Tyler's Ground, Loughborough|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=21 January 2013}}</ref> with [[W. G. Grace]] taking nine wickets in the North's first-innings and [[William Mycroft]] taking six wickets in the South's first-innings. Grace then took five wickets in the North's second-innings, ending with match figures of 14/108, while Mycroft took eight wickets in the South's second-innings to finish with match figures of 14/38. No batsman passed 26 runs, with the highest innings score being 130 in the North's second-innings. The match ended in a victory by 125 runs for the North.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/1/1994.html|title=North v South, 1875|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=21 January 2013}}</ref> No further matches are recorded as being played at the ground following this date and its location is today agricultural fields.
